### <a name="code-2" href="#code-2">Code fonts 2.0</a>

Further illustrating the potential of modern font usage across the desktop and web, the concept of [ligatures](link) has emerged for monospaced code fonts.

Take the font [Fria Code](https://github.com/tonsky/FiraCode), it improves the readability of common code expressions and strings:
- <span class="monospaced">!=&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> <span class="monospaced-ligatrues">-> !=</span>
- <span class="monospaced">www&nbsp;</span> <span class="monospaced-ligatrues">-> www</span>
- <span class="monospaced">***&nbsp;</span> <span class="monospaced-ligatrues">-> ***</span>
- <span class="monospaced">?=&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> <span class="monospaced-ligatrues">-> ?=</span>

These ligatures help with visual smoothness, readability and discernments of repetitive characters (i.e. <span class="monospaced-ligatrues">`**`</span> vs <span class="monospaced-ligatrues">`***`</span>)

There is some controversy about how adding ligatures can dilute truth when syntax is gospel but, in general, the trend of code ligatures shows potential. It‚Äôs still fairly new, first appearing in earnest [in 2015](https://medium.com/larsenwork-andreas-larsen/ligatures-coding-fonts-5375ab47ef8e) and you can now [easily graft programming ligatures onto many monospaced fonts](https://github.com/ToxicFrog/Ligaturizer).

